deltas.text: A capacitor stores energy in the form of an electric field.
Its ability to store energy (capacitance) is measured in Farads.
This circuit is currently disconnected, so no current is flowing into the capactor.
A capacitor obeys the relation Q=CV, where Q is the charge stored on its plates, C is its capacitance, and V is the voltage across the capacitor.
Differentiating, we have I=C*dV/dt, an alternative way of expressing this relation.
When this circuit connects, the capacitor will begin charging. As more charge accumulates on the capacitor, the voltage drop across it will increase.
After some time, the capacitor has charged to the point where the current flowing into it is negligible.
In general, after a capacitor has charged for 'a long time', it can be considered an open circuit for purposes of analysis.
The energy stored (different from power!) in a capacitor is equal to CV^2/2, in this case, 5.76 mJ. [END]
